Reference-contexts: MeshView contains a suite of options to provide the user with complete interactive control. The module is part of a data-flow based computational steering system, SciRun, used for the interactive control of science and engineering boundary value problems. <ref> [1] </ref>. SciRun provides MeshView with standard viewing capabilites such as rotation, translation, and scaling. METHODS MeshView allows the user to choose from a variety of different options for exploring the mesh. These include clipping isosurfaces and a growth algorithm, each with several attributes the user can change. <p> By allowing the user to explore the mesh in different ways, the program gives the user the information needed to understand the spatial relationships be tween the 3D elements. RESULTS Data enters MeshView via SciRun, the computational steering program <ref> [1] </ref>. Set up within SciRun is a map consisting of an input module, computation module (s), and an output module. In this case, the input module reads in the data points and connectivities of the mesh. The computation module contains the algorithms developed for MeshView.
